,Recommended,221020,12031424,"Posted: 8 September, 2014",all,Zstan,"Ok, first off, I just want to say that this review should be taken with a pinch of salt. This game has had an intense history for the time it's been around, and after witnessing a fair bit of it first-hand, I can say it wasn't pretty. I'll explain further on, as it does actually have a small amount to do with this review, but for now, let's get to it: Is the game good, and what's it about?What is Towns?: Towns is a top-down isometric strategy-RPG-simulation thingymabob. Most easily compared to Dwarf Fortress, it contains similar mechanics but without as much complexity. You control a small group of townies which require food, shelter, and equipment to survive. The world contains many dangers that will constantly threaten your civilization as you explore the underground dungeon for sweet loot, and farm the terrain to create vast fields of food. Everything can be controlled with your mouse with ease, from planting and building to digging and fighting. Of course, if you want to use those hotkeys to be a bit faster, then I don't blame you. You'll probably need them. While the art style may not be to everyone's taste, it's easy on the eyes and makes the world interesting to look at, providing you with plenty of colors to play with and enjoy.Reasons it's good: I've personally been a big fan of games like these since I found dwarf fortress a while back. So, I decided to pick this game up on sale and give it a bash. And I can honestly say I had fun. The overall simplicity of it made it easy for me to jump into it and understand most of what was going on right off the bat (though that may be in-part from having played similar games before-hand). The game looks pretty good most of the time, the blocks you can use to build have a lot of variation and color to them, so you can create some really nice looking builds. The A.I. has been a bit derpy sometimes, and I found myself often needing to fiddle with what my townies were doing regularly, but that's kinda what you'd expect to put up with when going into a game like this. When it boils down to it, I don't think towns is a game meant to be played with a hardcore mindset like one would play Dwarf Fortress with. The game is a lot simpler, and I found it to be a good game to play on my laptop in bed before going to sleep.Reasons it's bad: Now, some of the things that were good about it, worked kind of liked a double-edged sword. Yes, I had to fiddle with my little civilization, but it wasn't on things I wanted to do. Usually I had to deal with occasionally derpy A.I. that did silly things like leave items laying around that needed to be stored, or not building things correctly. Granted, these were problems I had some time ago. I haven't played much of the game recently (which I'll explain why in a moment), so I do believe some of those A.I. issues may have been resolved. The art style, while nice and simple, is maybe too simple, and could've used something to make it feel a bit more... energetic maybe? I guess beauty lies in the eyes of the beholder, but I think most people would agree that it's not a fabulous looking game. Good, but not fabulous. The simplicity, while nice for this game, could've used a few more things. Maybe a quest system, or thirst. Perhaps bigger maps would've even helped. Just some stuff to make it feel a bit meatier is all. Now, if you haven't figured it out yet, you should be wary of the game's history. If you want to dig deeper into it, go read the game's forums or discussions in the community hub. A VERY small summary of it could be boiled down to: The dev's got burnt out, people got upset, game slowed to a near-death crawl, and hasn't really recovered. The updates are few and far between, mostly consisting of bug fixes and patches. So don't be too hopeful about new content for the game, since in all likelihood, this is about as close as it'll get to a final product.Final Thoughts: I really, really can't hate too much on this game. I had fun with it for the time I played it, and I got my money's worth. But I can't whole heartedly recommend it either (at least at full price), so if it's on sale for a few bucks, then by all means, pick it up and give it a shot. I really only lost ~5$ on the deal, so I'm not too sour about it. For 5$, it was a nice, relatively relaxing game. There is the issue of the game's future though. Honestly, I'm not going to be the optimist, because from what I've seen and heard, optimism won't change much, if anything. I will say though, that I don't believe calling the game dead or abandoned is suitable either. Perhaps we can say that the game has become a husk, an empty shell of sorts. Or perhaps even more correct, would be to say it's a game that's suffered grievous wounds. The game has a chance to recover, and to stand back on its own two feet. Will it ever be what people hoped for? I doubt it. Will the community ever fully recover? Probably not. But, sometimes these things happen. Being too optimistic for something that very well may end up as a dead game is just as harmful as calling it dead outright. I'd love to see this game get built upon, and see amazing thigns happen. But after the toxicity I've witnessed, I'm not sure it's realistic to expect this game to be any more than a game you play in bed for an hour or two to chill to with some music in the background and a nice beverage. So if the game's ever on sale, and you need a nice game to fall asleep to (Warning: do not fall asleep to this game. Shut it off, and THEN go to sleep, lest your town become a graveyard), then pick it up for a few bucks and maybe buy a new CD from your favorite band with the money you saved. Like I said earlier though, take this review with a pinch of salt. While it is much simpler than Dwarf Fortress, it still has those FUN* mechanics in there under the layers of color, loot, and vast quantities of skootenbeeten. If you're not into the idea of watching everything you build up die from rogue werepigs, then buy with caution.Side Note: As it is somewhat important, it should be noted that the lead developer has been the focus of a lot of the controversy surrounding this title. While this should not be a major factor in your decision of buying/not buying this game, I do recommend at least making yourself aware of the situation with the developers. The details can be found by hunting around in the forums and whatnot, but here's a small summary to at least give you an idea: The toxicity of the community can really be traced back to the almost non-existant PR of the developers. After tensions rose, the lead developer was accused of basically taking the money and running, leaving behind a game that to most people (myself included) seemed like little more than an early access title. After minimal updates, and a new Dev that didn't stick around, things weren't looking good for the game, and still aren't. So if you have problems with supporting a company that made some mistakes from day 1, and ended up making themselves look untrustworthy, then take an extra pinch of salt with your final decision. I do believe though that the game should be viewed as it is, which at this point is something more closely relatable to a game you'd play in bed as I said earlier, without believing that it's a horrible piece of abandonware. 'Cus really it's not. It's a small game, not meant to be played on a bigger, more hardcore scale. It's got enough depth to keep you busy for a few hours at least, but not enough to really justify spending elongated hours on it. Regardless of what the developers did, or what the community says, it's a nice little pick up to add to your library for a couple bucks on sale."
,Not Recommended,221020,1654014,"Posted: 27 July, 2013",all,Cyanidekoolaid,"Towns could be a great game. It has a lot going for it. From the unique perspective to pleasing graphics it has the base to be a enjoyable time sink. Unfortunately the execution leaves a bit to be offered.The game itself is quite good. You control a group of townspeople who have started a town that happens to be on top of an active dungeon system. You go through the usual gathering and building phases, but are also tasked with dealing with monsters. As you begin to dig into the earth looking for resources you find caverns and tunnels populated by the genres classic baddies. Everything from spiders to ogres await you hapless townsfolk as they dig deeper. You have to build up a guard force to keep you town safe from these creatures, and at a certain point you can even attract ""adventurers"" that are much more powerful and able to really beat down some baddies. It's a fun mix of dungeon discovery and building and offers quite a bit of content as is.The bad part of it is that you can only pretty much count on it ""as is"" the ""early access"" part of this game is seriously slow. There have been exceptionally long gaps between developments, at some points even rumors development had stopped. Issues between developer and publisher have not helped things. So if you're willing to shell out for the game as it is now you will get quite a bit of content, just don't rest any solid hopes on it advancing. The chances of it ever actually being finished and brough inline with the initial goal of  the game is even less.Because of the issues I simply cannot recommend this game to someone. If there were regular updates and some progress towards completion I would completely back this game, but as I can't recommend a game I don't think is ever going to be completed for someone to buy."
